{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4842290c-3c8a-4f46-bf02-c88dc16cc1df","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** with .NET 9. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; } = default!;\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // Synchronous init (runs before each test)\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init (runs before each test, after sync init)\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest() { }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — use a public **property** with `{ get; set; }`. MSTest auto-injects it before each test.\n- **Sync init** — use `[TestInitialize]` returning `void`.\n- **Async init** — use a *separate* `[TestInitialize]` method returning `Task`. MSTest 3.x supports multiple `[TestInitialize]` methods.\n- **Constructor** — can also be used for simple sync setup, but `TestContext` won't be available there yet (it's set after construction).\n\nFor **class-level** one-time setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (also supports async):\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static async Task ClassSetup(TestContext context)\n{\n    // Runs once before all tests in the class\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b6c8f98b-2436-4413-94f9-da028755f20d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. Let me check the latest MSTest documentation to give accurate advice. In MSTest v3, the recommended pattern has evolved significantly:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest 3.x, `TestContext` can be injected via constructor (preferred) rather than the old property-based approach.\n\n2. **Initialization**: MSTest 3.x supports:\n   - `[TestInitialize]` for synchronous init (can also be async)\n   - `[ClassInitialize]` for class-level init\n   - Constructor for simple synchronous init\n   \nFor version 3.8.2 specifically, constructor injection of `TestContext` is the modern approach, and `[TestInitialize]` can now return `Task` for async operations, so I can recommend combining both patterns depending on what they're initializing.","outputTokens":695,"requestId":"702F:2ADC27:BD6D94:DB9CF4:69F2B099"},"id":"c6768573-4096-43dd-934f-5b27c9484aa0","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:30:16.547Z","parentId":"d6f88c76-e3d1-4bf3-98ab-2ce1a3bddce8"}
